REPRINT from the Southwest edition of the Press Enterprise, Newspaper, -----------------------------------------------------------<br>
ONCE THEY WERE WARRIORS<br><br>
Thirty years ago they were fighting for their lives at a Vietnam river. Friday, they were swapping tales in a VFW hall.<br>
----------------------------------------------------------<br>
By David E. Hendrix<br>
The Press Enterprise<br>
Saturday February 8, 1997<br>
----------------------------------------------------------<br><br>
Thirty years ago the men were young Marines, fighting battle-savvy North Vietnamese regulars at the river bend for the right to life.<br><br>
Friday, they were 10 middle-aged men hugging, some with tears in their eyes, resurrecting bonds created in the life-and-death grind of the Vietnam War.<br><br>
For most, three decades had passed since last sharing a beer, a rumor, or a thought with any of the former infantrymen laughing and joking in the Veterans of Foreign Wars Post in Glen Avon. But to each, Friday’s timing was perfect.<br><br>
The reunion, which continues through the weekend in Big Bear, is the idea of R.M. “Cook” Barela of Jurupa, known locally as a community activist, former school board member and minister of a home church. To the members of the 1st platoon, India Company, 3rd Battalion, 7th Marines, he is one of two machine gunners who helped defeat a superior force in 1967 and has now reunited his comrades.<br><br>
“This group of people didn’t talk to others when they came home,” said Lawrence Wilson a retired FBI agent who was the platoon’s lieutenant and leader. “Only now have a few started reaching out.”<br><br>
Many were only teen-agers when they returned from Vietnam, but aged by 14 months of war.<br><br>
It was November 8, 1967, when a North Vietnamese battalion raided the Dai Loc District of South Vietnam and killed 300 civilians. The Marines’ 173-member “I Company, including the 47 men in the 1st platoon, took part in Operation Foster, a search for the raiders.<br><br>
They met the enemy at a bend in the Song Thu Bon River, 15 miles southwest of DaNang, where about 300 Vietnamese ambushed the 1st platoon, according to Marine records. The fight lasted for six hours before reinforcements; persistence and casualties cast the conflict in the Marines’ favor.<br><br>
All but seven of the 1st platoon members were wounded. Communist troops dubbed I Company “The Marine Suicide Unit” because of its tenacity.<br><br>
Friday, the warriors were mellow. Their hair brushed with various shades of gray, they came from New York, Wyoming, Montana, Colorado, Missouri, Utah and throughout California. The group includes a correction officer, soil scientist, forklift operator, pest controller, commercial pilot and a disabled boat rigger.<br><br>
Herman “Izzie” LazJeunesse of Hudson Wyo., a Shoshone Indian, was partially paralyzed in the Sung Thu Bon River battle by a bullet that pierced his left side and went out the right. His friend, Newman “Chief” Cuch, a Ute Indian also from Hudson, carried him to an evacuation zone and guarded him for four hours before he could be lifted out.<br>
LaJeunese was shipped to a Wyoming veterans hospital where he defied predictions and walked again in a month and a half. He toured the hospital’s corridors at night, using handrails for support, because he was too self-conscious to work out in daylight.<br><br>
LaJeunesse now uses a cane for support. Friday, he and Cuch sat down after hugging their former comrades, sipped their beers, and savored the moment. LaJeunesse trains horses and supervises a chariot-racing business. Cuch operates a gas and oil-drilling rig.<br><br>
“It makes my eyes water” LaJeunesse said of the gathering. “I’ve raced chariots all this time. This is more exciting.”<br>
Barela said the reunion grew out of a writing project he began more than a year ago and hopes to end soon with a book. He fished out a diary he kept in Vietnam, worked three months transcribing the notes and cried when he read the last chapter. He had to find his comrades.<br>
Friday’s gathering was the result.<br><br>
Dennis Martinez of Burbank, the other machine gunner, was the first to show up at the VFW hall. He quietly waited at the bar for the others.<br><br>
“I’m so nervous, I hope I do this right,” the general contractor said. He was the first man Barela contacted. The men joined forces to hunt down others.<br>
“Thank God for the Internet,” Martinez said. “I don’t know where we’d be without it.”<br><br>
Yes, thanks for the internet, I've gotten to meet all of you. Once we were warriors and it seems like we still are today.<br><br>
Cook
